=begin pod

=head1 3. Connecting to an LLM

The C<normalize-text> function is the bridge between free-form English and the
canonical DSL the grammar can parse.

=head2 How it works

=begin code :lang<raku>
use LLM::Functions;

sub normalize-text(Str $text --> Str) {
    my &normalizer = llm-function(
        -> :$input {
            qq:to/PROMPT/.trim
            Convert this restaurant booking text into the DSL format shown.

            Example input:  Jane booked a table for 4 at 7:30pm tomorrow at Bistro Verde
            Example output: name "Jane" party 4 time 19:30 restaurant "Bistro Verde" date tomorrow

            Rules:
            - name: full name in double quotes
            - party: integer number of people
            - time: 24-hour HH:MM
            - restaurant: full name in double quotes
            - date: single word or ISO date

            Respond with ONLY the DSL line, no explanation.

            Input: $input
            PROMPT
        },
        llm-evaluator => 'chatgpt'
    );
    ~normalizer(input => $text)
}
=end code

=head2 The three-part pipeline

=item B<Prompt goes in> — free-form English from the user
=item B<LLM normalizes> — converts to the canonical DSL line
=item B<Grammar parses> — extracts typed, named captures

This separation is the key insight: the LLM handles natural language
variation; the grammar enforces structure. Neither has to do the other's job.

=head2 Putting it together

=begin code :lang<raku>
sub parse-booking(Str $text --> Str) is export {
    my $canonical = normalize-text($text);
    my $match = Slangify::Tutorial::Grammar.parse(
        $canonical,
        :actions(Slangify::Tutorial::Actions.new)
    );
    die "Could not parse: '$canonical'" unless $match;
    $match.made.raku
}
=end code

The C<parse-booking> sub chains normalization → grammar → actions in one call
and returns a JSON string.

=end pod
